  group_by(zip_code) %>%
  summarise(zme = median(price)) %>%

The steps of inference are: Gather a representative sample from a population Establish the null/alternative hypothesis (the research question) Set confidence level 1 to balance Type I & II errors is the risk level Test the hypothesis for practical and statistical significance based on the sample practical significance: How big is the impact or difference of the variable(s)? statistical significance: How consistent or reliable is the difference? State the results

10.1 View Rank

  • Null: View has no influence on property value

    • True null: view rank does not impact value
    • False null: view rank does impact sales
    • Type 1: reject true null - ask more for property based on view (inepensive, if expensive use small alpha)
    • Type 2: fail to reject false null - dont consider view in appraisal (expensive, use large alpha)

Alternative: View has an influence on property value

vchi <- chisq.test(df$view, df$price)
## Warning in stats::chisq.test(x, y, ...): Chi-squared approximation may be
## incorrect
vchi
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  df$view and df$price
## X-squared = 17162, df = 14496, p-value < 2.2e-16

10.1.1 Practical Significance

summary(df$view)
##     0     1     2     3     4 
## 19489   332   963   510   319

There are fewer properties with views than non-view properties. The small sample size may not be practically or significantly significant

10.1.2 Statistical Significance

The property values are statistically different in relation to view rank with a P value of less than 0.001. Therefore we reject the null hypothesis that property values are not related to view

Non-technical: A properties view ranking has an impact on the propertys value Technical: Property values are statistically different for different view ranks with a P value of less than 0.001

10.2 Waterfrontage

  • Null: Water frontage has no influence on property value Alternative: Water frontage has an influence on property value

    • True null: water frontage does not impact value
    • False null: waterfrontage does impact sales
    • Type 1: reject true null - ask more for property based on water frontage (inepensive, if expensive use small alpha)
    • Type 2: fail to reject false null - dont consider water frontage in appraisal (expensive, use large alpha)

Alternative: Water frontage has an influence on property value

wchi <- chisq.test(df$waterfront, df$price)
## Warning in stats::chisq.test(x, y, ...): Chi-squared approximation may be
## incorrect
wchi
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  df$waterfront and df$price
## X-squared = 5953, df = 3624, p-value < 2.2e-16

10.2.1 Practical Significance

summary(df$waterfront)
##     0     1 
## 21450   163

There are only 163 waterfront sales out of 21613 total sales. The sample size is too small to be practically significant

10.2.2 Statistical Significance

Waterfront property values are statistically different from non-waterfront with a p value of less than 0.001. We reject the null hypothesis that waterfront does not influence property value.

Non-technical: Water frontage has an impact on property value Technical: Water front property values are statistically different with a P value of less then 0.001
